I got stuck because of how hard to find the routes and puzzles in this game (also because of the fighting mechanism actually), and then ... I came to this video looking for guide. I'm impressed... you're really pro at playing this game, but when you make a walkthrough video like this, IMO you're spending too much time on unnecessary things. If you want to make a walkthrough video, then you should just stay objective.

Just run through "the cute enemies" (you know what i mean) and only face the boss or mini-boss that seals the door or that gives you objective items, stop looking for unimportant items (except objective items like keys and others), don't go to the unimportant area, stop interacting with NPC that the dialogue doesn't affect the storyline. Only do the main missions/quest from the main storyline in the game (of course with 3 endings for Sekiro Shadows Die Twice).

That way you will save your recording time and save your viewer's time that looking for guide. That is what's called a "walkthrough gameplay video" and how it works.
Anyway ... good game, well played.

Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice is a 2019 action-adventure game developed by FromSoftware and published by Activision. It was released for PlayStation 4, Windows, and Xbox One in March 2019, and for Stadia in October 2020. The game follows a shinobi known as Wolf, who attempts to take revenge on a samurai clan that imprisoned him and kidnapped his lord. The gameplay is focused on stealth, exploration, and combat, with a particular emphasis on boss battles. It takes place in a fictionalized Japan during the Sengoku period and makes strong references to Buddhist mythology and philosophy.

Lead director Hidetaka Miyazaki wanted to create a new intellectual property (IP) that marked a departure from their Dark Souls series, looking at games such as Tenchu for inspiration. Sekiro was praised by critics, who complimented its gameplay and setting, and compared it to Dark Souls, although opinions on its difficulty were mixed. It won several year-end awards and sold over five million copies by July 2020
